'''Alexander 'Sandy' Wiseman MacAra''' (4 May 1932 – 21 June 2012) {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRCP|FRCGP}}<ref name=RCPfellow>{{cite web|title=Sir Alexander Wiseman Macara|url= http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/6527 |accessdate=11 May 2014|publisher=RCPLondon}}</ref> was a Scottish professor of [[epidemiology]] at [[University of Bristol|Bristol University]] and chairman of [[British Medical Association]] (BMA) from 1993 to 1998.<ref name=BMJ_obit>{{cite journal|last=Davies|first=Peter|title=Obituary – Alexander MacAra|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=345|pages=e4644|date=9 July 2012|doi=10.1136/bmj.e4644}}</ref><ref name=Ind_profile>{{cite news|last=O'Sullivan|first=Jack|title=Profile: Scalpel to blunt an axe: Dr Sandy MacAra: He is leading the BMA out of the sickroom. But where to?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/profile-scalpel-to-blunt-an-axe-dr-sandy-MacAra-he-is-leading-the-bma-out-of-the-sickroom-but-where-to-jack-osullivan-reports-1412918.html|accessdate=4 May 2014|newspaper=The Independent|date=10 July 1994}}</ref>

== Early life ==
Alexander Wiseman MacAra was born on 4 May 1932 in [[Irvine, North Ayrshire]], Scotland.<ref name=TelegraphObit1>{{cite news|last=Obituary|title=Sir Sandy MacAra|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/9363152/Sir-Sandy-MacAra.html|accessdate=4 May 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=28 June 2012}}</ref> Both his father and grandfather were Presbyterian ministers.<ref name="Guardian obituary">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/aug/06/sir-sandy-macara |title=Sir Sandy Macara obituary |work=The Guardian |date=6 August 2012 |accessdate=21 February 2016}}</ref> Marion, his mother, was a civil servant. When he was six years old, MacAra was treated for paratyphoid fever, acute appendicitis and whooping cough.<ref name=TelegraphObit1 /> Growing up he witnessed the public health affects of the slums in Glasgow as well as the health problems of the dockers and miners.<ref name=NPG>{{cite web|title=Alexander Wiseman MacAra (1932–), Epidemiologist and teacher of medicine (portrait by Nick Sinclair)|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp08489/alexander-wiseman-MacAra|publisher=National Portrait Gallery|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>

He was educated at [[Irvine Royal Academy]].<ref name="Guardian obituary"/> He studied at the [[University of Glasgow Medical School|Glasgow Medical School, Glasgow University]], graduating with a [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|medical degree]] in 1958.<ref name=RCPE_obit>{{cite web|title=Obituaries&nbsp;– Sir Sandy (Alexander Wiseman) Macara, FRCP Edin|url=http://www.rcpe.ac.uk/obituary/sir-sandy-alexander-wiseman-MacAra-frcp-edin|publisher=Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh (RCPE)|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> He went on to gain a [[Professional degrees of public health#United Kingdom|DPH]] from the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] in 1960.<ref name=RCPE_obit />

== Early career ==
* 1963 – 1997 Lecturer in Public Health, and later Consultant Senior Lecturer in Public Health, Bristol University<ref name=TelegraphObit1 />
* 1960s Founding member and subsequently Head of Department of Epidemiology and Public Health Medicine, Bristol University<ref name=TelegraphObit1 />

== Career ==
From 1993 to 1998 MacAra was the chair of the ruling council of British Medical Association (BMA). He was consultant to the World Health Organisation (for over 20 years ), and he was president of the National Heart Forum.<ref name=TelegraphObit1 /> He was a member of the Council of the [[General Medical Council]] (GMC)

== Campaigning ==
He played a key role in smoking ban in public places which was introduced in 2007. In 2009 he called for the [[MMR vaccine]] to be made compulsory following an unfounded health scare which resulted in a fall in the take up rate of the vaccine within the UK.<ref name=TelegraphObit1 />

== Honours ==
* [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians#Membership and Fellowship|Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians (FRCP)]]<ref name=TelegraphObit1 />
* 1992 Honorary Doctor of Public Health, Athens<ref name=RCPE_obit />
* Knighthood 1997<ref name=TelegraphObit1 />

== Personal life ==
MacAra was married to Sylvia and they had two children, a daughter, Alexandra, and a son, James.<ref name=BBC_Obit>{{cite news|title=Former BMA chairman Sir Sandy Macara dies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-18580265|accessdate=4 May 2014|newspaper=BBC News (Bristol)|date=25 June 2012}}</ref> He died on 21 June 2012.<ref name=BBC_Obit/>

